===Hurricane Arlene===
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Hurricane Arlene
| category=cat1
| type=hurricane
| image=Arlene 22 aug 1987 1737Z.jpg
| track=Arlene 1987 track.png
| formed=[[August 10]]
| dissipated=[[August 28]]
| highest winds=75&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (120&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=987&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
A low pressure system on the tail end of a stationary cold front organized into a [[subtropical]] depression on [[August 8]] near the [[South Carolina]] coast, and drifted southward.<ref name="ArleneTCRPg1">
{{cite web
| author=Harrold P. Gerrish
| year=[[1987-10-16]]
| title=Preliminary Report: Hurricane Arlene - Page 1 - Storm History I
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/arlene/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> Convection organized more, and the storm was classified Tropical Depression Three on [[August 10]] over the [[Bahamas]]. It executed an anticyclonic loop to the northeast, and was estimated to have attained tropical storm status on [[August 11]], based on reports from [[Hurricane Hunters]]. Small cells in the ridge of high pressure caused Arlene to take an unusual track to the east, with two southward jogs in its path.<ref name="ArleneTCRPg1"/> A [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] of low pressure near [[Bermuda]] initially inhibited strengthening. However, after high pressures to its east forced the storm northward, more favorable conditions allowed Arlene to intensify into a hurricane on [[August 22]].<ref name="ArleneTCRPg2">
{{cite web
| author=Harrold P. Gerrish
| year=[[1987-10-16]]
| title=Preliminary Report: Hurricane Arlene - Page 2 - Storm History II, Meteorological Statistics, Impact and Conclusion
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/arlene/prelim02.gif
}}</ref> Operationally, it was upgraded two days earlier, based on the appearance of an [[eye (cyclone)|eye feature]] on satellite imagery. After becoming a hurricane, Arlene accelerated to the northeast into the cold waters of the north [[Atlantic Ocean]], and on [[August 23]] it became [[extratropical cyclone|extratropical]] about halfway between [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] and [[Ireland]]. The extratropical remnants turned to the southeast and later to the east, making landfall on the [[Iberian Peninsula]] before dissipating on [[August 28]] over [[Spain]].<ref name="ArleneTCRPg2"/>

As Arlene approached, islanders of [[Bermuda]] were warned to board up their homes, with winds of {{convert|50|mi/h|km/h|-1|abbr=on}} expected.<ref name="Arlene-News1">
{{cite web
| author=The Miami Herald
| year=[[1987-08-13]]
| title=BERMUDA BOARDS UP FOR ARLENE
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367CA760B4795&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref> Ultimately, the island experienced winds of {{convert|35|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} with gusts up to {{convert|49|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name="ArleneTCRPg2"/> A 41-year old blind sailor on a trip across the Atlantic was unable to make it to a harbor in [[Bermuda]] due to the hurricane, and rode out the storm in the open sea.<ref name="Arlene-News2">
{{cite web
| author=The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution 
| year=[[1987-08-13]]
| title=Blind sailor to ride out storm at sea
| publisher=The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7C2D79EA3903E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM 
}}</ref> The storm produced moderate rainfall to coastal areas of [[Spain]], contributing to a monthly rainfall record at Rota.<ref name="ArleneTCRPg2"/><ref name="MWR">
{{cite web
| author=Harrold P. Gerrish and Robert Case
| date=[[April]] [[1988]]
| title=1987 Monthly Weather Review
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://ams.allenpress.com/archive/1520-0493/116/4/pdf/i1520-0493-116-4-939.pdf
}}</ref> The 14.5 day total between the start of its best track and when it attained hurricane status is the largest on record for an [[Atlantic hurricane]].<ref name="hurdat">{{cite web|author=NHC Hurricane Research Division|title=Atlantic hurricane best track|publisher=NOAA| date=[[2006-02-17]]|accessdate=2007-04-04|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/easyhurdat_5105.html}}</ref>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Depression Four===
{{storm path needed}}
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Depression Four
| category=depression
| type=tropical depression
| image=TD 4L 14 aug 1987 1900Z.jpg
| formed=[[August 14]]
| dissipated=[[August 15]]
| highest winds=35&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (55&nbsp;[[kilometers per hour|km/h]])
}}
A tropical depression formed off the coast of [[Antigua]] on [[August 14]].<ref name="TD4-1">
{{cite news
| date=[[1987-08-15]]
| title=Arlene bashes Bermuda; new storm develops
| publisher=The Daily Herald
}}</ref> There were chances that the depression could strengthen, but that did not occur. Tropical Depression Four peaked at 35 mph (55 km/h) and dissipated on [[August 15]].<ref name="TD4-2">
{{cite news
| date=[[1987-08-15]]
| title=Tropical depression - No threat to Jamaica
| publisher=The Gleaner
