===Tropical Storm Bret===
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Storm Bret
| category=storm
| type=tropical storm
| image=Bret 20 aug 1987 1755Z.jpg
| track=Bret 1987 track.png
| formed=[[August 17]]
| dissipated=[[August 24]]
| highest winds=50&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (80&nbsp;[[kilometers per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
A well-organized tropical disturbance formed off the [[African]] coast on [[August 17]] and became a tropical depression the following day, as classified by satellite imagery.<ref name="BretTCR">
{{cite web
| author=Gilbert B. Clark
| date=[[September]] [[1987]]
| title=Preliminary Report: Tropical Storm Bret
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/bret/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> Later the same day, the ship S.S. Columbus Canterrury reported {{convert|40|mi/h|km/h|-1|abbr=on}} winds and a minimal pressure of 1004 millibars, and the depression became Tropical Storm Bret.

The cyclone moved a westward course of 20 - {{convert|25|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} and reached its peak intensity of 50 [[mph]] and 1000 [[millibars]] on [[August 20]].<ref name="BretTCR"/> A ridge of high pressure in the eastern [[Atlantic Ocean]], north of Bret, began to weaken and drift to the east on the 20th. The storm was moving at {{convert|17|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} to the east on [[August 21]]. It was thought that Bret would strengthen at this point.<ref name="BRET - NEWS1">
{{cite web
| author=Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-08-21]]
| title=STORM NO. 2 IS EXPECTED TO INTENSIFY BRET 1,400 MILES FROM CARIBBEAN
| publisher=Miami Herald 
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367D5E4677294&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM 
}}</ref> Bret slowed from [[August 21]] until [[August 23]], moving at only 15 - 20 [[mph]].<ref name="BretTCR"/> The cyclone soon moved on a northwestward course and encountered wind shear. Bret weakened into a depression on [[August 23]], due to the wind shear over the system. The next morning, the depression became a tropical wave with no low-level circulation left. The wave was soon absorbed by a trough of low pressure during the next few days. Bret never affected land, during its existence.<ref name="BretTCR"/>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Depression Six===
{{storm path needed}}
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Depression Six
| category=depression
| type=tropical depression
| image=TD 6L 31 aug 1987 1736Z.jpg
| formed=[[August 31]]
| dissipated=[[September 4]]
| highest winds=35&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (55&nbsp;[[kilometers per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
A tropical depression formed off the African coast on [[August 31]], in which forecasters predicted would become the third tropical storm of the season.<ref name="TD6-1">
{{cite web
| author=Miami Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-09-02]]
| title=STORM WEAKENS, STILL GOING WEST
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB368194DBCAB9B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref> At 6 [[Ante Meridiem|AM]] [[August 31]], the depression was seemingly appeared unchanged, staying at winds of about 35 mph (55 km/h). The depression was then located {{convert|825|nmi|km|0}} west of Sao Taigo in the [[Cape Verde Islands]], stirring up {{convert|12|ft|m|0|sing=on}} seas.<ref name="TD6-2">
{{cite web
| author=Miami Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-09-04]]
| title=FIZZLING DEPRESSION DOWNGRADED TO TROPICAL WAVE
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36819B52CA2FB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM 
}}</ref> 

The next day, Tropical Depression Six moved eastward becoming {{convert|1050|mi|km|0}} off the Cape Verde Islands, too far for the National Hurricane Center to send a reconnaissance flight into the depression.<ref name="TD6-3">
{{cite news
| date=[[1987-09-01]]
| title=Tropical Depression Drifts Westward
| publisher=The Daily Intelligencer
}}</ref> Tropical Depression Six was at the time not a threat to land and few ships were in the area.<ref name="TD6-4">
{{cite web
| author=Miami Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-08-31]]
| title=DEPRESSION OFF AFRICA IS LIKELY TO BECOME STORM
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367E5826AAC06&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref> Tropical Depression Six degenerated into a tropical wave on [[September 4]], never affecting land or reaching storm-intensity. Redevelopment was possible, but that did not occur.<ref name="TD6-5">{{cite news |title= September begins on a Cool Note |publisher=[[Syracuse-Herald Journal]]|date=[[1987-09-01]]|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Storm Cindy===
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Storm Cindy
| category=storm
| type=tropical storm
| image=Cindy 7 sept 1987 1622Z.jpg
| track=Cindy 1987 track.png
| formed=[[September 5]]
| dissipated=[[September 10]]
| highest winds=50&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (80&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
On [[September 1]] a [[tropical wave]] exited the [[Africa]]n coast, and moved westward across the Atlantic Ocean.<ref name="CindyTCR">
{{cite web
| author=National Hurricane Center
| year=[[1987-10-03]]
| title=Tropical Storm Cindy Tropical Cyclone Report
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/cindy/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> A trough of low pressure moved southeastward through the tropics, and brought the wave more towards the north. Generally favorable conditions for development allowed the wave to organize into a tropical depression on [[September 5]], and two days later it attained tropical storm status. Cindy continued northward, and peaked at {{convert|50|mi/h|km/h|-1|abbr=on}} winds on the 8th before turning to the northeast. Strong upper-level shear weakened the storm, and after two days of struggling as a tropical storm, Cindy became [[extratropical]] on the 10th to the northwest of the [[Azores]].<ref name="CindyTCR"/> 

Cindy did not affect any landmasses.<ref name="CindyTCR"/>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Depression Eight===
{{storm path needed}}
{{infobox hurricane small
 |name=Tropical Depression Eight
| category=depression
| type=tropical depression
| image=TD 8L 6 sept 1987 1956Z.jpg
| formed=[[September 5]]
| dissipated=[[September 8]]
| highest winds=35&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (55&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
A tropical depression formed in the [[Caribbean Sea]] on [[September 5]]. It tracked westward through the body of water, and reached  peak winds of 35&nbsp;mph (55&nbsp;km/h) on [[September 7]].<ref name="TD8-2">
{{cite web
| author=The Miami Herald
| year=[[1987-09-07]]
| title=DEPRESSION STRENGTHENS
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367E8005E574F&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref><ref name="TD8-3">
{{cite news
| first=Daily Herald
| date=[[1987-09-08]]
| title=Forecasters watch tropical depressions
| publisher=Daily Herald
}}</ref> Despite its well-organized appearance, Tropical Depression Eight failed to develop further and dissipated on [[September 8]].<ref name="TD8-4">
{{cite news
| first=Aiken Standard
| date=[[1987-09-08]]
| title=Potential Hurricane Is Over Wilmington
| publisher=Aiken Standard
}}</ref> 
<div style="clear:both;"></div>

===Tropical Depression Nine===
{{storm path needed}}
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Depression Nine
| category=depression
| type=tropical depression
| image=TD 9L 7 sept 1987 1950Z.jpg
| track=Td91987rain.gif
| formed=[[September 6]]
| dissipated=[[September 10]]
| highest winds=35&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (55&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
An upper-level cyclone in the northern [[Gulf of Mexico]] spurred [[tropical cyclogenesis]] offshore the southeast [[United States]]. Convection organized around a low pressure area east of [[Florida]], and it was declared Tropical Depression Nine on [[September 7]]. Initially poorly organized,<ref name="TD9-4">
{{cite web
| author=Chicago Sun-Times
| year=[[1987-09-08]]
| title=Tropical depression forms off South Carolina
| publisher=Chicago Sun-Times
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36D852CE940E1&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM 
}}</ref> the depression moved generally northward without strengthening, and quickly made landfall along the coast of [[South Carolina]]. It maintained its identity as it tracked through [[North Carolina]] and the [[Mid-Atlantic States]], and on [[September 10]] the depression merged with a [[surface weather analysis|frontal wave]] over [[New England]]. The cyclone dropped moderate precipitation along its path, peaking at 10.27&nbsp;inches in central [[Virginia]]; stations in [[Maryland]], the [[Carolinas]], and [[Pennsylvania]] reported over 5&nbsp;inches (125&nbsp;mm) of rainfall.<ref name="TD9-Rains">
{{cite web
| author=David Roth
| year=2007
| title=Tropical Depression 9 Rainfall Summary
| publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/td9of1987.html  
}}</ref> [[Flash flood]] warnings were issued in some localities due to the precipitation, and in [[Virginia]] over 50&nbsp;roads were washed out.<ref name="TD9-4">
{{cite web
| author=The Miami Herald
| year=[[1987-09-09]]
| title=DEPRESSION WEAKENS OVER NORTH CAROLINA
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367EC885EC5B0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref> Slick roads caused three tractor-trailers to jackknife along a 2&nbsp;mile (3&nbsp;km) portion of the [[Interstate 495 (Capital Beltway)|Capital Beltway]]. Additionally, four&nbsp;people required rescue assistance after being trapped in swollen creeks.<ref name="TD9-5">
{{cite web
| author=Eve Zibart
| year=[[1987-09-09]]
| title=Rain-Slicked Beltway Spawns Wrecks and Traffic Tie-Ups
| publisher=The Washington Post
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/73844001.html?dids=73844001:73844001&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=SEP+09%2C+1987&author=Eve+Zibart&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=Rain-Slicked+Beltway+Spawns+Wrecks+and+Traffic+Tie-Ups&pqatl=google
}}</ref>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Storm Dennis===
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Storm Dennis
| category=storm
| type=tropical storm
| image=Dennis 11 sept 1987 1719Z.jpg
| track=Dennis 1987 track.png
| formed=[[September 8]]
| dissipated=[[September 20]]
| highest winds=50&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (80&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
A tropical depression formed on [[September 8]] off the coast of [[Africa]]. It tracked westward, passing to the south of the [[Cape Verde]] islands, and based on satellite imagery was estimated to have reached tropical storm status on [[September 10]]. Tropical Storm Dennis continued to gradually intensify, and on [[September 11]] attained peak winds of 50&nbsp;mph (80&nbsp;km/h) and a minimum pressure of 1000&nbsp;mbar (hPa). Subsequently the cyclone weakened to minimal tropical storm status,<ref name="DennisTCR">
{{cite web
| author=Miles B. Lawrence
| year=[[1987-10-06]]
| title=Preliminary Report: Tropical Storm Dennis
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/dennis/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> and by [[September 14]], Dennis was expected to immediately weaken to tropical depression status.<ref name="Dennis-News1">
{{cite web
| author=San Jose Mercury News
| year=[[1987-09-14]]
| title=TROPICAL STORM LIKELY TO WEAKEN
| publisher=San Jose Mercury News
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SJ&s_site=mercurynews&p_multi=SJ&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB72C50DF5ECF3B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref> However, Dennis remained a minimal tropical storm for four more days before deteriorating to a tropical depression on [[September 18]], as reported by a [[Hurricane Hunters]] plane. The depression turned abruptly northwestward through a weakness in the [[subtropical ridge]], suggesting a new [[low pressure area]] developed. On [[September 19]] it turned to the northeast, and on [[September 20]] Dennis merged with an [[extratropical cyclone|extratropical low]].<ref name="DennisTCR"/>

<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Depression Eleven===
{{storm path needed}}
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Depression Eleven
| category=depression
| type=tropical depression
| image=TD 11L 14 sept 1987 1829Z.jpg
| formed=[[September 14]]
| dissipated=[[September 16]]
| highest winds=35&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (55&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1000&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
On [[September 14]], a tropical depression developed about 490&nbsp;miles (790&nbsp;km) southeast of [[Antigua]]. Tracking westward at 5&ndash;10&nbsp;mph (8&ndash;16&nbsp;km/h), the depression maintained winds of about 35&nbsp;mph (55&nbsp;km/h), and was deemed "no cause for alarm" for the [[Lesser Antilles]].<ref name="TD11-1">{{cite web
| author=Miami Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-09-15]]
| title=FARAWAY DENNIS, NEWEST DEPRESSION NO CAUSE FOR ALARM
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367F843A37782&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref><ref name="TD11-2">
{{cite web
| author=Miami Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-09-14]]
| title=NEW STORM THREATENING IN ATLANTIC
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367F8E1E514AE&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref> Failing to intensify further, the depression degenerated into a [[tropical wave]] on [[September 16]] to the east of Antigua. No damage of fatalities were reported.<ref name="TD11-3">
{{cite web
| author=Miami Herald Staff
| year=[[1987-09-16]]
| title=DEPRESSION FIZZLES INTO TROPICAL WAVE
| publisher=The Miami Herald
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB367F9F8723A2F&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM
}}</ref>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Hurricane Emily===
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Hurricane Emily
| category=cat3
| type=hurrricane
| image=Emily 22 sept 1987 1206Z.jpg
| track=Emily 1987 track.png
| formed=[[September 20]]
| dissipated=[[September 26]]
| highest winds=125&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (205&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=958&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
{{hurricane main|Hurricane Emily (1987)}}
A tropical storm formed east of the [[Windward Islands]] and headed westward, later causing considerable damage on [[Saint Vincent (island)|Saint Vincent]].<ref name="EmilyTCR1">
{{cite web
| author=Harrold P. Gerrish
| year=[[1987-11-12]]
| title=Hurricane Emily Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 1
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/emily/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> The cyclone then slowly began turning north, soon making landfall in the [[Dominican Republic]], where three people were reported dead and there was $30 million (1987 [[US dollars]]) in damage. Emily passed over [[Hispaniola]], turned to the northeast, and eventually made landfall in [[Bermuda]], where it caused $35 million (1987 USD) in damage, though there were no fatalities.<ref name="EmilyTCR4">
{{cite web
| author=Harrold P. Gerrish
| year=[[1987-11-12]]
| title=Hurricane Emily Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 4
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/emily/prelim04.gif
}}</ref> 
Thousands of migratory birds took refuge on Bermuda during the storm, including ten thousand [[bobolink]]s and thousands of [[Connecticut warbler]]s.  After the storm passed Bermuda, Emily became the fastest moving hurricane of the previous century, moving at a pace of {{convert|69|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} or 31 m/s.

Emily was the first hurricane in the [[Caribbean Sea]] since [[Hurricane Katrina (1981)|Hurricane Katrina]] of the [[1981 Atlantic hurricane season]].<ref name="EmilyTCR1"/>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Hurricane Floyd===
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Hurricane Floyd
| category=cat1
| type=hurrricane
| image=Floyd 12 oct 1987 1313Z.jpg
| track=Floyd 1987 track.png
| formed=[[October 9]]
| dissipated=[[October 13]]
| highest winds=75&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (120&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=993&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
{{hurricane main|Hurricane Floyd (1987)}}
A broad area of low pressure organized into a tropical depression off the coast of [[Nicaragua]] on [[October 9]]. After drifting to the southeast, it turned to the north-northwest and organized into a tropical storm on [[October 10]]. After crossing western [[Cuba]], Floyd accelerated to the northeast, and attained hurricane status late on [[October 12]]. It passed through the [[Florida Keys]] before entraining cooler, drier air from a stationary frontal boundary.<ref name="FloydTCR1">
{{cite web
| author=Gilbert B. Clark
| year=[[1987-10-27]]
| title=Hurricane Floyd Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 1
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/floyd/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> Its convection became very disorganized, and Floyd weakened back to a tropical storm early on [[October 13]] to the southeast of [[Miami, Florida|Miami]]; the storm crossed the [[Bahamas]], and becoming an [[extratropical cyclone]] before being absorbed by the frontal boundary on [[October 14]].<ref name="FloydTCR2">
{{cite web
| author=Gilbert B. Clark
| year=[[1987-10-27]]
| title=Hurricane Floyd Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 2
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/floyd/prelim02.gif
}}</ref>

Damage in Florida was minimal, due to the disorganized nature of the hurricane. Floyd brought up to 10.07 inches to the state, causing moderate crop damage in the southern portion of the state.<ref name="FloydRain">{{cite web| author=David Roth| year=[[2007]]| title=Hurricane Floyd - October 10-13, 1987| publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center| accessdate=2007-10-11| url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/floyd1987.html}}</ref><ref name="FloydTCR3"/> In addition, a tornado spawned by the storm damaged portions of the Florida Keys. Overall damage amounted to around $500,000 (1987 [[USD]]), with no casualties or injuries reported.<ref name="FloydTCR3">{{cite web| author=Gilbert B. Clark| year=[[1987-10-27]]| title=Hurricane Floyd Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 3| publisher=National Hurricane Center| accessdate=2007-10-11| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/floyd/prelim03.gif
}}</ref>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

===Tropical Depression Fourteen===
{{storm path needed}}
{{infobox hurricane small
| name=Tropical Depression Fourteen
| category=depression
| type=tropical depression
| image=TD 14L 31 oct 1987 2008Z.jpg
| formed=[[October 31]]
| dissipated=[[November 4]]
| highest winds=35&nbsp;[[miles per hour|mph]] (55&nbsp;[[kilometres per hour|km/h]])
| lowest pressure=1004&nbsp;[[mbar]] ([[hPa]])
}}
{{hurricane main|Tropical Depression Fourteen (1987)}}
A broad area of low pressure existed in the central [[Caribbean Sea]] in late October. It steadily organized, and was classified as Tropical Depression Fourteen on [[October 31]]. It moved northwestward, and entered a high-shear environment due to an upper level low situated toward the end of a high pressure system. By [[November 1]], little convection remained as the weak depression turned to the north and crossed [[Cuba]]. A burst of convection organized over the depression, and brought strong wind gusts to the [[Florida Keys]] as it passed through the area on the 2nd.<ref name="FourteenTCR1">
{{cite web
| author=National Hurricane Center
| year=[[1987-11-17]]
| title=Tropical Depression Fourteen Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 1
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/trop/prelim01.gif
}}</ref> It continued to the north-northwest, paralleling the [[Florida]] west coast, and lost all of its convection on the 3rd. The system turned to the northeast, and merged with a weak [[extratropical]] low over northern Florida on the 4th.<ref name="FourteenTCR2">
{{cite web
| author=National Hurricane Center
| year=[[1987-11-17]]
| title=Tropical Depression Fourteen Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 2
| publisher=National Hurricane Center
| accessdate=2007-10-11
| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/trop/prelim02.gif
}}</ref>

While passing to the west of [[Jamaica]], the depression dropped heavy rainfall, with a three-day peak of 10.21&nbsp;[[inches]] (25.93&nbsp;[[millimeter|mm]] at [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], and a peak daily rainfall total of 6.38&nbsp;inches (16.21&nbsp;mm) on [[November 1]].<ref name="FourteenTCR4">{{cite web| author=National Hurricane Center| year=[[1987-11-17]]| title=Tropical Depression Fourteen Tropical Cyclone Report - Page 4| publisher=National Hurricane Center| accessdate=2007-10-11| url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1987-prelim/trop/prelim04.gif}}</ref> According to an unofficial report, the flooding caused six fatalities in Jamaica.<ref name="MWR"/> [[Cuba]] reported moderate rainfall, peaking at 4.75&nbsp;inches (12.07&nbsp;mm) in [[Bah<U+00ED>a Honda, Cuba|Bah<U+00ED>a Honda]] the province of [[Pinar del R<U+00ED>o Province|Pinar del R<U+00ED>o]].<ref name="FourteenTCR4"/> Despite being a weak system, the depression also dropped moderate precipitation across [[Florida]], peaking at 10.23&nbsp;inches (26&nbsp;mm) at [[Loxahatchee National Wildlife Refuge]]. Rainfall was experienced as far north as eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and extreme southern [[South Carolina]].<ref name="TD14-Rains">
{{cite web
| author=David Roth
| year=2007
| title=Tropical Depression 14 Rainfalls
| publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center
| accessdate=2007-04-04
| url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/td141987.html  
}}</ref>
<div style="clear: both"></div>

