The table on the right shows the [[Accumulated Cyclone Energy|ACE]] for each storm in the season. ACE is, broadly speaking, a measure of the power of the hurricane multiplied by the length of time it existed, so storms that last a long time, as well as particularly strong hurricanes, have high ACEs. ACE is only calculated for full advisories on tropical systems at or exceeding 34&nbsp;knots (39&nbsp;mph, 63&nbsp;km/h) or tropical storm strength.
{{clear}}

==Storm names==
The following names were used for named storms that formed in the north Atlantic in 1987. This is the same list used for the [[1981 Atlantic hurricane season|1981 season]]. No names were retired, so it was used again in the [[1993 Atlantic hurricane season|1993 season]]. Names that were not assigned are marked in {{tcname unused}}.

{| width="90%" style="clear:both;"
|
* Arlene
* Bret
* Cindy
* Dennis
* [[Hurricane Emily (1987)|Emily]]
* [[Hurricane Floyd (1987)|Floyd]]
* {{tcname unused|Gert}}
|
* {{tcname unused|Harvey}}
* {{tcname unused|Irene}}
* {{tcname unused|Jose}}
* {{tcname unused|Katrina}}
* {{tcname unused|Lenny}}
* {{tcname unused|Maria}}
* {{tcname unused|Nate}}
|
* {{tcname unused|Ophelia}}
* {{tcname unused|Philippe}}
* {{tcname unused|Rita}}
* {{tcname unused|Stan}}
* {{tcname unused|Tammy}}
* {{tcname unused|Vince}}
* {{tcname unused|Wilma}}
|}

=== Retirement ===
{{seealso|List of retired Atlantic hurricane names}}
The [[World Meteorological Organization]] retired no names used in the 1987 season.

